# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: arch-linux
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] Pacman, a package manager written specifically for Arch Linux, is used to install, remove and update software packages.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] The Arch User Repository (AUR) serves as a community-driven software repository for Arch Linux and provides packages not included in the official repositories and alternative versions of packages; AUR packages can be downloaded and built manually, or installed through an AUR 'helper'.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] Arch Linux has comprehensive documentation in the form of a community-run wiki known as the ArchWiki.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] Inspired by CRUX, another minimalist distribution, Judd Vinet began the Arch Linux project in March 2002.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] The name was chosen because Vinet liked the word's meaning of "the principal," as in "arch-enemy".
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] Originally only for IA-32 (32-bit x86) CPUs, the first x86-64 installation standard ISO image was released in April 2006.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] Vinet led Arch Linux until 1 October 2007, when he stepped down due to lack of time, transferring control of the project to Aaron Griffin.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] Until Pacman version 4.0.0, Arch Linux's package manager lacked support for signed packages.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] Packages and metadata were not verified for authenticity by Pacman during the download-install process.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] Without package authentication checking, tampered-with or malicious repository mirrors could compromise the integrity of a system.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] Pacman 4 allowed verification of the package database and packages, but it was disabled by default.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] In November 2011, package signing became mandatory for new package builds, and as of March 2012, every official package is signed.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] In June 2012, package signing verification became official and is now enabled by default in the installation process.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] The migration to systemd as its init system began in August 2012, and it became the default on new installations in October 2012.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] It replaced the SysV-style init system, used since the distribution's inception.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] The end of i686 support was announced in January 2017, with the February 2017 ISO being the last one including i686 and making the architecture unsupported in November 2017.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] Since then, the community derivative Arch Linux 32 can be used for i686 hardware.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] On 24 February 2020, Aaron Griffin announced that due to his limited involvement with the project, he would, after a voting period, transfer control of the project to Levente Polyak.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] This change also led to a new 2-year term period being added to the Project Leader position.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] In March 2021, Arch Linux developers were thinking of porting Arch Linux packages to x86_64-v3, roughly correlating to the Intel Haswell era of processors.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] In April 2021, Arch Linux installation images began including a guided installation script called 'archinstall' by default.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] In late 2021, the Arch Linux developers released Pacman 6.0, which enabled parallel downloads.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] In February 2022, the Arch Linux developers began offering debug packages.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] In September 2024, Valve partnered with Arch Linux developers to support ongoing development efforts with the focus on build service infrastructure and secure signing enclave.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] On 14 August 2025, the Arch User Repository, the Arch Linux Forums and the Arch Linux website were hit by a distributed denial-of-service attack.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] As a result of the attack web services became temporarily unavailable and downloads from the AUR were severely slowed down or impossible.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] Arch is largely based on binary packages.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] Packages target x86-64 microprocessors to assist performance on modern hardware.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] A ports/ebuild-like system is also provided for automated source compilation, known as the Arch build system.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] This is largely achieved by encouraging the use of succinctly commented, clean configuration files that are arranged for quick access and editing.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] This has earned it a reputation as a distribution for "advanced users" who are willing to use the command-line interface.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] The current Arch Linux logo was designed by Thayer Williams in 2007 as part of a contest to replace the previous logo.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] The Arch Linux website supplies ISO images that may be burned to a CD or USB drive.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] Installation can be accomplished manually by following the instructions on the Arch Wiki, or automatically through the use of the included "archinstall" script.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] Another command line utility that comes bundled with the installation media, "pacstrap" may be used to install the base system.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] Installation of additional packages which are not part of the base system can be done with either pacstrap, Pacman after booting (or chrooting) into the new installation, or by specifying packages within the guided archinstall script.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] An alternative to using CD or USB images for installation is to use the static version of the package manager Pacman, from within another Linux-based operating system.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] The user can mount their newly formatted drive partition, and use pacstrap (or Pacman with the appropriate command-line switch) to install base and additional packages with the mountpoint of the destination device as the root for its operations.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] This method is useful when installing Arch Linux onto USB flash drives, or onto a temporarily mounted device which belongs to another system.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] Depending on the selected installation type, further actions may need to be taken before the new system is ready for use.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] Notable configuration includes the installation of a bootloader, configuring the system with a hostname, network connection, language settings, and graphical user interface.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] Arch Linux does not schedule releases for specific dates, nor does it provide traditional releases, but instead uses a rolling release model.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] Packages in the main repositories are updated often, with new updates being pushed far quicker when compared to long-term support (LTS) distributions.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] This style of package management allows systems to remain updated easily.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] Occasionally, manual interventions are needed for certain updates, with instructions posted on the news section of the Arch Linux website.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] All packages are managed through pacman, a package manager written specifically for Arch Linux.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] Pacman handles package installation, upgrades, downgrades, removal and features automatic dependency resolution.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] The packages for Arch Linux are obtained from the Arch Linux package tree and are compiled for the x86-64 architecture.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] Pacman typically uses binary packages with a `.tar.zst` extension (for zstd compression), with `.pkg` placed before this to indicate that it is a Pacman package (giving `.pkg.tar.zst`); though other compression formats are also valid, such as `.pkg.tar.xz`.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] Packages can be installed via `pacman -S *package name*`, and `pacman -Syu` can be used to perform a full system upgrade.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] As well as Arch Linux, Pacman is also used for installing packages under MSYS2 (a fork of Cygwin) on Windows.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] Also, *testing* repositories exist which include binary package candidates for other repositories.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] The *core-staging* and *extra-staging* repositories are used for some rebuilds to avoid broken packages in *testing*.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] There are also two other repositories that include the newest version of certain desktop environments.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] The *unstable* repository was dropped in July 2008 and most of the packages moved to other repositories.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] The *community* repository was merged with *extra* in May 2023.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] In addition to the official repositories, there are a number of unofficial user repositories.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] The most well-known unofficial repository is the Arch User Repository, or AUR, hosted on the Arch Linux site.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] The AUR does not host binary packages but instead a collection of build scripts known as PKGBUILDs.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] PKGBUILD scripts are executed by the `makepkg` command, which downloads the necessary files from the software's repository and builds them using the Arch build system.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] The Arch Linux repositories contain both libre and nonfree software, and the default Arch Linux kernel contains nonfree proprietary blobs, hence the distribution is not endorsed by the GNU project.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] The linux-libre kernel can be installed from the AUR or by enabling Parabola's repositories.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] The Arch build system (ABS) is a ports-like source packaging system that compiles source tarballs into binary packages, which are installed via Pacman.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] The Arch build system provides a directory tree of shell scripts, called *PKGBUILDs*, that enable any and all official Arch packages to be customized and compiled.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] Rebuilding the entire system using modified compiler flags is also supported by the Arch build system.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] The Arch build system `makepkg` tool can be used to create custom `pkg.tar.zst` packages from third-party sources.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] The resulting packages are also installable and trackable via Pacman.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] For packages not provided in the official repositories, the Arch User Repository (AUR) provides user-made PKGBUILD bash scripts which retrieve and build source code or binaries from non-Arch Linux sources.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] PKGBUILD scripts cannot be downloaded or run by pacman, but they contain all the necessary instructions and metadata to build packages which pacman can install.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] Unofficial AUR helper programs, like Yay or Paru, can automate installation from the AUR.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] However, because scripts not validated by any trusted person may be uploaded to the AUR, Arch developers have stated that utilities for automatic finding, downloading and executing of PKGBUILDs, including AUR helpers, will never be included in the official repositories.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] Arch Linux directs users to acquaint themselves with the process of vetting PKGBUILDs, including when using AUR helpers.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] Instances of malware have been discovered in the past, such as on 19 July 2025 when a modified Firefox build contained a Remote access trojan.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] On 12 June 2026, Arch announced "a high volume of malicious package adoptions and updates in the Arch User Repository", and a list of 1579 affected packages was posted later that day.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] The attack consisted of edits to PKGBUILDs adding installation instructions for malicious npm packages.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] Two days later several packages containing obfuscated malware code, russian spam and profanities are also found and fixed.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] Package Maintainers, official Arch Linux staff, are charged with "keeping the AUR in working order".
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] They maintain popular packages, communicate with and send patches to developers of packaged software, screen PKGBUILDs for malware, and vote on administrative matters.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] Arch Linux is working on making all official packages reproducible.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] This means that when a package is rebuilt in a different environment it should be bit-by-bit identical.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] This allows users and researchers to verify the integrity of the packages found in the official repository.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] The status of this effort can be monitored on the dedicated status page.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] The Arch Linux wiki maintains its own list of Arch-based distributions.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] There are several projects working on porting the Arch Linux ideas and tools to other kernels, including PacBSD (formerly ArchBSD) and Arch Hurd, which are based on the FreeBSD and GNU Hurd kernels, respectively.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] Artix Linux is based on Arch, and avoids using systemd.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] Instead, users can choose alternatives like OpenRC, runit, s6, and dinit.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] Manjaro is an Arch-based distro designed to be easy to use.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] Unlike vanilla Arch, Manjaro is designed with both beginners and experienced users in mind.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] EndeavourOS is a terminal-centric distro based on Arch, and the successor of the discontinued Antergos.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] Garuda Linux is a gamer-focused distro based on Arch.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] SteamOS 3.0, the version of SteamOS used in the Steam Deck by Valve, is based on Arch Linux.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] CachyOS is a Linux distribution based on Arch Linux with changes and optimizations intended to improve performance on newer hardware, prioritizing gaming, among other tasks.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] As of March 2026, CachyOS is the most popular desktop distro on ProtonDB, overtaking Arch Linux.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] OSNews also has five later reviews about Arch Linux.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] LWN.net wrote a review about Arch Linux in 2005.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] LWN.net also has two later reviews about Arch Linux.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] Tux Machines reviewed Arch Linux in 2007.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] Chris Smart from DistroWatch Weekly wrote a review about Arch Linux in January 2009.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] DistroWatch Weekly reviewed Arch Linux again in September 2009 and in December 2015.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] The Linux kernel developer and maintainer Greg Kroah-Hartman (GKH) has stated that he uses Arch Linux and that it "works really really well".
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] He has also praised the Arch Wiki, the distribution's rolling release model, and the feedback loop with the community.
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] In a 2023 DistroWatch poll, about half of the responders maintained that they were running either Arch (17%) or an Arch derivative (30%).
[src:arch-linux/arch-linux] As of 2025, Arch also enjoys the third highest average rating of any Linux distribution on DistroWatch with a rating of 9.18, with only two higher rated distributions (Artix Linux and BigLinux) also being Arch derivatives.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] A **Linux distribution**, often abbreviated as **distro**, is an operating system that includes the Linux kernel for its kernel functionality.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] Although the name does not imply product distribution per se, a distro—if distributed on its own—is often obtained via a website intended specifically for the purpose.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] Distros have been designed for a wide variety of systems ranging from personal computers (for example, Linux Mint and Zorin OS) to servers (for example, Red Hat Enterprise Linux) and from embedded devices (for example, OpenWrt) to supercomputers (for example, Rocks Cluster Distribution).
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] A distro typically includes many components in addition to the Linux kernel.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] Commonly, it includes a package manager, an init system (such as systemd, OpenRC, SysVinit, or runit), GNU tools and libraries, documentation, IP network configuration utilities, the getty TTY setup program, and many more.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] Typically, most of the included software is free and open-source software – made available both as binary for convenience and as source code to allow for modifying it.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] A distro may also include proprietary software that is not available in source code form, such as a device driver binary.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] A distro may be described as a particular assortment of application and utility software (various GNU tools and libraries, for example), packaged with the Linux kernel in such a way that its capabilities meet users' needs.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] The software is usually adapted to the distribution and then combined into software packages by the distribution's maintainers.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] The software packages are available online in repositories, which are storage locations usually distributed around the world.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] Beside "glue" components, such as the distribution installers (for example, Debian-Installer and Anaconda) and the package management systems, very few packages are actually written by a distribution's maintainers.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] Distributions have been designed for a wide range of computing environments, including desktops, servers, laptops, netbooks, mobile devices (phones and tablets), and embedded systems.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] There are commercially backed distributions, such as Red Hat Enterprise Linux (Red Hat), openSUSE (SUSE) and Ubuntu (Canonical), and entirely community-driven distributions, such as Debian, Slackware, Gentoo and Arch Linux.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] Most distributions come ready-to-use and prebuilt for a specific instruction set, while some (such as Gentoo) are distributed mostly in source code form and must be built before installation.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] Linus Torvalds developed the Linux kernel and distributed its first version, 0.01, in 1991.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] Linux was initially distributed as source code only, and later as a pair of downloadable floppy disk images: one bootable and containing the Linux kernel itself, and the other with a set of GNU utilities and tools for setting up a file system.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] Since the installation procedure was complicated, especially in the face of growing amounts of available software, distributions sprang up to simplify it.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] The two oldest, still active distribution projects started in 1993.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] The SLS distribution was not well maintained, so in July 1993 a new SLS-based distribution, Slackware, was released by Patrick Volkerding.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] Also dissatisfied with SLS, Ian Murdock set to create a free distribution by founding Debian in August 1993, with first public BETA released in January 1994 and first stable version in June 1996.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] Users were attracted to Linux distributions as alternatives to MS-DOS compatible operating systems, Windows, Classic Mac OS, and proprietary versions of Unix.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] Most early adopters were familiar with Unix from work or school.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] They embraced Linux distributions for their low (or absent) cost, and the availability of the source code for most or all of their software.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] As of 2025, Linux has become more popular in server and embedded devices markets than in the desktop market.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] It is used in approximately 64.5% of web servers; its current operating system market share is about 2.51%, and its desktop operating system market share is about 2.94%.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] Many Linux distributions provide an installation system akin to that provided with other modern operating systems.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] Other distributions, including Gentoo Linux, provide only the binaries of a basic kernel, compilation tools, and an installer; the installer compiles all the requested software for the specific architecture of the user's computer, using these tools and the software's source code.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] Distributions are normally segmented into *packages*.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] Each package contains a specific application or service.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] Examples of packages are a library for handling the PNG image format, a collection of fonts, and a web browser.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] The package is typically provided as compiled code, with installation and removal of packages handled by a package management system (PMS) rather than a simple file archiver.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] Each package intended for such a PMS contains meta-information such as its description, version number, and its dependencies (other packages it requires to run).
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] The package management system evaluates this meta-information to allow package searches, perform automatic upgrades to newer versions, and to check that all dependencies of a package are present (and either notify the user to install them, or install them automatically).
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] The package can also be provided as source code to be compiled on the system.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] Most distributions install packages, including the kernel and other core operating system components, in a predetermined configuration.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] A few now require or permit configuration adjustments at first install time.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] This makes installation less daunting, particularly for new users, but is not always acceptable.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] For specific requirements, much software must be carefully configured to be useful, to work correctly with other software, or to be secure, and local administrators are often obliged to spend time reviewing and reconfiguring it.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] Some (but not all) distributions go to considerable lengths to adjust and customize the software they include, and some provide configuration tools to help users do so.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] By obtaining and installing *everything* normally provided in a distribution, an administrator may create a "distribution less" installation.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] It is possible to build such systems from scratch, avoiding distributions altogether.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] One needs a way to generate the first binaries until the system is *self-hosting*.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] This can be done via compilation on another system capable of building binaries for the intended target (possibly by cross-compilation).
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] The diversity of Linux distributions is due to technical, organizational, and philosophical variation among vendors and users.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] The permissive licensing of free software means that users with sufficient knowledge and interest can customize any extant distribution, or design one to suit their own needs.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] Rolling Linux distributions are kept current using small and frequent updates.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] The terms *partially rolling* and *partly rolling* (along with synonyms *semi-rolling* and *half-rolling*), *fully rolling*, *truly rolling* and *optionally rolling* are sometimes used by software developers and users.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] Repositories of **rolling distributions** usually contain very recent software releases—often the latest stable versions available.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] They have pseudo-releases and installation media that are simply snapshots of the distribution at the time of the installation image's release.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] Typically, a rolling-release OS installed from older installation medium can be fully updated after it is installed.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] Depending on the usage case, there can be pros and cons to both standard release and rolling release software development methodologies.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] In terms of the software development process, **standard releases** require significant development effort to keep old versions up-to-date by propagating bug fixes back to the newest branch, versus focusing on the newest development branch.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] Also, unlike rolling releases, standard releases require more than one code branch to be developed and maintained, which increases the workload of the software developers and maintainers.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] On the other hand, software features and technology planning are easier in standard releases due to a better understanding of upcoming features in the next version(s).
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] Software release cycles can also be synchronized with those of major upstream software projects, such as desktop environments.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] As for the user experience, standard releases are often viewed as more stable and bug-free since software conflicts can be more easily addressed and the software stack more thoroughly tested and evaluated, during the software development cycle.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] For this reason, they tend to be the preferred choice in enterprise environments and mission-critical tasks.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] However, rolling releases offer more current software which can also provide increased stability and fewer software bugs along with the additional benefits of new features, greater functionality, faster running speeds, and improved system and application security.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] Regarding software security, the rolling release model can have advantages in timely security updates, fixing system or application security bugs and vulnerabilities, that standard releases may have to wait till the next release for or patch in various versions.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] In a rolling release distribution, where the user has chosen to run it as a highly dynamic system, the constant flux of software packages can introduce new unintended vulnerabilities.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] A "live" distribution is a Linux distribution that can be booted from removable storage media such as optical discs or USB flash drives, instead of being installed on and booted from a hard disk drive.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] The portability of installation-free distributions makes them advantageous for applications such as demonstrations, borrowing someone else's computer, rescue operations, or as installation media for a standard distribution.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] When the operating system is booted from a read-only medium such as a CD or DVD, any user data that needs to be retained between sessions cannot be stored on the boot device but must be written to another storage device, such as a USB flash drive or a hard disk drive.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] Many Linux distributions provide a "live" form in addition to their conventional form, which is a network-based or removable-media image intended to be used only for installation; such distributions include antiX, SUSE, Ubuntu, Linux Mint, MX Linux and Fedora Linux.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] Some distributions, including Knoppix, Puppy Linux, Devil-Linux, SuperGamer, SliTaz GNU/Linux and dyne:bolic, are designed primarily for live use.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] Additionally, some minimal distributions can be run directly from as little space as one floppy disk without the need to change the contents of the system's hard disk drive.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] The website DistroWatch lists many Linux distributions and displays some of the ones that have the most web traffic on the site.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] The Wikimedia Foundation released an analysis of the browser User Agents of visitors to WMF websites until 2015, which includes details of the most popular Operating System identifiers, including some Linux distributions.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] Many of the popular distributions are listed below.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] Whether such operating systems count as a "Linux distribution" is a controversial topic.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] They use the Linux kernel, so the Linux Foundation and Chris DiBona, Google's former open-source chief, agree that Android is a Linux distribution; others, such as Google engineer Patrick Brady, disagree by noting the lack of support for many GNU tools in Android, including glibc.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] Other Linux-kernel-based operating systems include Tizen, Mer/Sailfish OS, KaiOS and Amazon's Kindle firmware.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] Lightweight Linux distributions are those that have been designed with support for older hardware in mind, allowing older hardware to still be used productively, or, for maximum possible speed in newer hardware by leaving more resources available for use by applications.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] Examples include antiX, Damn Small Linux (based on antiX), Tiny Core Linux, Puppy Linux and Slitaz.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] The Free Standards Group was an organization formed by major software and hardware vendors that aims to improve interoperability between different distributions.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] Among their proposed standards are the Linux Standard Base, which defines a common ABI and packaging system for Linux, and the Filesystem Hierarchy Standard which recommends a standard file naming chart, notably the basic directory names found on the root of the tree of any Linux filesystem.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] Those standards, however, see limited use, even among the distributions developed by members of the organization.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] The diversity of Linux distributions means that not all software runs on all distributions, depending on what libraries and other system attributes are required.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] Packaged software and software repositories are usually specific to a particular distribution, though cross-installation is sometimes possible on closely related distributions.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] One of solutions for interdistribution issues, particularly to run software created for a distribution on another, is by using container such as Distrobox.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] There are several ways to install a Linux distribution.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] The most popular method of installing Linux is by booting from a live USB memory stick, which can be created by using a USB image writer application and the ISO image, which can be downloaded from various Linux distribution websites.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] DVD disks, CD disks, network installations and even other hard drives can also be used as "installation media".
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] In the 1990s, Linux distributions were installed using sets of floppy disks, but this has been abandoned by all major distributions.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] By the 2000s, many distributions offered CD and DVD sets with the vital packages on the first disk and less important packages on later ones.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] Some distributions, such as Debian also enabled installing over a network after booting from either a set of floppy disks or a CD with only a small amount of data on it.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] New users tend to begin by partitioning a hard drive to keep their formerly installed operating system.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] The Linux distribution can then be installed on its own separate partition without affecting formerly saved data.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] In a Live CD setup, the computer boots the entire operating system from CD without first installing it on the computer's hard disk.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] Many distributions have a Live CD *installer*, where the computer boots the operating system from the disk, and it can then be installed on the computer's hard disk, providing a seamless transition from the OS running from the CD to the OS running from the hard disk.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] Both servers and personal computers that come with Linux already installed are available from vendors including Hewlett-Packard, Dell and System76.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] On embedded devices, Linux is typically held in the device's firmware and may or may not be consumer-accessible.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] Anaconda, one of the more popular installers, is used by Red Hat Enterprise Linux, Fedora (which uses the Fedora Media Writer) and other distributions to simplify the installation process.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] Debian, Ubuntu and many others use Debian-Installer.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] The process of constantly switching between distributions is often referred to as "distro hopping".
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] Virtual machine software such as VirtualBox and VMware Workstation virtualize hardware allowing users to test live media on a virtual machine without installing to the real system.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] Some websites like DistroWatch offer lists of distributions, and link to screenshots of operating systems as a way to get a first impression of various distributions.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] Some distributions let the user install Linux on top of their current system, such as coLinux.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] Linux is installed to the Windows hard disk partition, and can be started from inside Windows itself.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] Virtual machines (such as VirtualBox or VMware Workstation) also make it possible for Linux to be run inside another OS.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] The VM software simulates a separate computer onto which the Linux system is installed.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] After installation, the virtual machine can be booted as if it were an independent computer.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] Some specific proprietary software products are not available in any form for Linux.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] As of September 2015, the Steam gaming service has over 1,500 games available on Linux, compared to 2,323 games for Mac and 6,500 Windows games.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] Emulation and API-translation projects like Wine and CrossOver make it possible to run non-Linux-based software on Linux systems, either by emulating a proprietary operating system or by translating proprietary API calls (e.g., calls to Microsoft's Win32 or DirectX APIs) into native Linux API calls.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] A virtual machine can also be used to run a proprietary OS (like Microsoft Windows) on top of Linux.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] Pre-built computers are usually sold with an operating system other than Linux already installed by the original equipment manufacturer (OEM).
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] This limits Linux's market share: consumers are unaware that an alternative exists, they must make a conscious effort to use a different operating system, and they must either perform the actual installation themselves, or depend on support from a friend, relative, or computer professional.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] However, it is possible to buy hardware with Linux already installed.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] Lenovo, Hewlett-Packard, Dell, Affordy, Purism, Pine64 and System76 all sell general-purpose Linux laptops.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] Custom-order PC manufacturers will also build Linux systems, but possibly with the Windows key on the keyboard.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] Fixstars Solutions (formerly Terra Soft) sold Macintosh computers and PlayStation 3 consoles with Yellow Dog Linux installed.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] It is more common to find embedded devices sold with Linux as the default manufacturer-supported OS, including the Linksys NSLU2 NAS device, TiVo's line of personal video recorders, and Linux-based cellphones (including Android smartphones), PDAs, and portable music players.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] The current Microsoft Windows license lets the manufacturer determine the refund policy.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] With prior versions of Windows, it was possible to obtain a refund if the manufacturer failed to provide the refund by litigation in the small claims courts.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] On February 15, 1999, a group of Linux users in Orange County, California held a "Windows Refund Day" protest in an attempt to pressure Microsoft into issuing them refunds.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] There are no official figures on the popularity, adoption, downloads or installed base of Linux distributions.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] There are also no official figures for the total number of Linux systems, partly due to the difficulty of quantifying the number of PCs running Linux (see Desktop Linux adoption), since many users download Linux distributions.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] Hence, the sales figures for Linux systems and commercial Linux distributions indicate a much lower number of Linux systems and level of Linux adoption than is the case; this is mainly due to Linux being free and open-source software that can be downloaded free of charge.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] A Linux Counter Project had kept track of a running guesstimate of the number of Linux systems, but did not distinguish between rolling release and standard release distributions.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] It ceased operation in August 2018, though a few related blog posts were created through October 2018.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] Desktop usage statistical reports for particular Linux distributions have been collected and published since July 2014 by the Linux Hardware Project.
[src:arch-linux/linux-distribution] Statcounter, a web traffic analysis company, within the *operating system market share*, showed that the Linux operating systems had, according to them, 3.9% of the worldwide market share in July 2025.
[src:arch-linux/rolling-release] A rolling release model is different from a staged or "staggered" rollout, in which an update is gradually made available to an increasing percentage of users for testing or bandwidth reasons.
[src:arch-linux/rolling-release] An example of a rolling release would be Arch Linux, where new packages and updates roll in constantly, and significant changes to the distribution may occur at any time by the developers.
[src:arch-linux/rolling-release] This is in contrast to Ubuntu Linux, which has biannual releases, with the only major changes after a release being security updates or significant bug fixes.
[src:arch-linux/rolling-release] Rolling release development models are one of many types of software release life cycles.
[src:arch-linux/rolling-release] Some modern Distributed SQL databases such as YugabyteDB also support this feature.
[src:arch-linux/rolling-release] A rolling release is typically implemented using small and frequent updates.
[src:arch-linux/rolling-release] However, simply having updates does not automatically mean that a piece of software is using a rolling release cycle; for this, the philosophy of developers must be to work with one code branch as opposed to discrete versions.
[src:arch-linux/rolling-release] When the rolling release is employed as the development model, software updates are typically delivered to users by a package manager on the user's personal computer, accessing through the internet a remote software repository (often via a download mirror) stored on an internet file server.
[src:arch-linux/source-code] In computing, **source code**, or simply **code** or **source**, is human readable plain text that can eventually result in controlling the behavior of a computer.
[src:arch-linux/source-code] In order to control a computer, it must be processed by a computer program – either executed directly via an interpreter or translated into a more computer-consumable form such as via a compiler.
[src:arch-linux/source-code] Sometimes, code is compiled directly to machine code so that it can be run in the native language of the computer without further processing.
[src:arch-linux/source-code] Many modern environments, though, involve compiling to an intermediate representation such as bytecode that can either run via an interpreter or be compiled on-demand to machine code via just-in-time compilation.
[src:arch-linux/source-code] The first programmable computers, which appeared at the end of the 1940s, were programmed in machine language (simple instructions that could be directly executed by the processor).
[src:arch-linux/source-code] Machine language was difficult to debug and was not portable between different computer systems.
[src:arch-linux/source-code] Initially, hardware resources were scarce and expensive, while human resources were cheaper.
[src:arch-linux/source-code] As programs grew more complex, programmer productivity became a bottleneck.
[src:arch-linux/source-code] This led to the introduction of high-level programming languages such as Fortran in the mid-1950s.
[src:arch-linux/source-code] These languages abstracted away the details of the hardware, and were designed to express algorithms that could be understood more easily by humans.
[src:arch-linux/source-code] As instructions distinct from the underlying computer hardware, software is therefore relatively recent, dating to these early high-level programming languages such as Fortran, Lisp, and Cobol.
[src:arch-linux/source-code] The invention of high-level programming languages was simultaneous with the compilers needed to translate the source code automatically into machine code that can be directly executed on the computer hardware.
[src:arch-linux/source-code] Source code is the form of code that is modified directly by humans, typically in a high-level programming language.
[src:arch-linux/source-code] Object code can be directly executed by the machine and is generated automatically from the source code, often via an intermediate step, assembly language.
[src:arch-linux/source-code] While object code will only work on a specific platform, source code can be ported to a different machine and recompiled there.
[src:arch-linux/source-code] For the same source code, object code can vary significantly—not only based on the machine for which it is compiled, but also based on performance optimization from the compiler.
[src:arch-linux/source-code] Most programs do not contain all the resources needed to run them and rely on external libraries.
[src:arch-linux/source-code] Part of the compiler's function is to link these files in such a way that the program can be executed by the hardware.
[src:arch-linux/source-code] Software developers often use configuration management to track changes to source code files (version control).
[src:arch-linux/source-code] The configuration management system also keeps track of which object code file corresponds to which version of the source code file.
[src:arch-linux/source-code] The number of source lines of code (SLOC) is often used as a metric when evaluating the productivity of computer programmers, the economic value of a code base, effort estimation for projects in development, and the ongoing cost of software maintenance after release.
[src:arch-linux/source-code] Source code is also used to communicate algorithms between parties, e.g., code snippets online or in books.
[src:arch-linux/source-code] Computer programmers can find it helpful to review extant source code to learn about programming techniques.
[src:arch-linux/source-code] The sharing of source code between developers is often cited as a contributing factor to the maturing of their programming skills.
[src:arch-linux/source-code] Some consider source code an expressive artistic medium.
[src:arch-linux/source-code] Source code often contains comments—blocks of text marked for the compiler to ignore.
[src:arch-linux/source-code] This content is not part of the program logic, but is instead intended to help readers understand the program.
[src:arch-linux/source-code] Companies often keep the source code confidential in order to hide algorithms considered a trade secret.
[src:arch-linux/source-code] Proprietary, secret source code and algorithms are widely used for sensitive government applications such as criminal justice, which results in black box behavior with a lack of transparency into the algorithm's methodology.
[src:arch-linux/source-code] The result is avoidance of public scrutiny of issues such as bias.
[src:arch-linux/source-code] Access to the source code (not just the object code) is essential to modifying it.
[src:arch-linux/source-code] Understanding extant code is necessary to understand how it works and before modifying it.
[src:arch-linux/source-code] The rate of understanding depends both on the code base as well as the skill of the programmer.
[src:arch-linux/source-code] Experienced programmers have an easier time understanding what the code does at a high level.
[src:arch-linux/source-code] Software visualization is sometimes used to speed up this process.
[src:arch-linux/source-code] Many software programmers use an integrated development environment (IDE) to improve their productivity.
[src:arch-linux/source-code] IDEs typically have several features built in, including a source-code editor that can alert the programmer to common errors.
[src:arch-linux/source-code] Modification often includes code refactoring (improving structure without changing function) and restructuring (improving structure and function simultaneously).
[src:arch-linux/source-code] Nearly every change to code introduces new bugs or unexpected ripple effects, which require another round of fixes.
[src:arch-linux/source-code] Code reviews by other developers are often used to scrutinize new code added to a project.
[src:arch-linux/source-code] The purpose of this phase is often to verify that the code meets style and maintainability standards and that it is a correct implementation of the software design.
[src:arch-linux/source-code] According to some estimates, code review dramatically reduce the number of bugs persisting after software testing is complete.
[src:arch-linux/source-code] Along with software testing that works by executing the code, static program analysis uses automated tools to detect problems with the source code.
[src:arch-linux/source-code] Many IDEs support code analysis tools, which might provide metrics on the clarity and maintainability of the code.
[src:arch-linux/source-code] Debuggers are tools that often enable programmers to step through execution while keeping track of which source code corresponds to each change of state.
[src:arch-linux/source-code] Source code files in a high-level programming language must go through a stage of preprocessing into machine code before the instructions can be carried out.
[src:arch-linux/source-code] After being compiled, the program can be saved as an object file and the loader (part of the operating system) can take this saved file and execute it as a process on the computer hardware.
[src:arch-linux/source-code] Some programming languages use an interpreter instead of a compiler.
[src:arch-linux/source-code] An interpreter converts the program into machine code at run time, which makes them 10 to 100 times slower than compiled programming languages.
[src:arch-linux/source-code] Source code was used this way to distribute the Unix operating system early in the history of Unix, and later to allow programs written in scripting languages (in particular the JavaScript client-side scripting language) to run on a wide variety of machines.
[src:arch-linux/source-code] Software quality is an overarching term that can refer to a code's correct and efficient behavior, its reusability and portability, or the ease of modification.
[src:arch-linux/source-code] It is usually more cost-effective to build quality into a product from the start rather than try to add it later in a development process.
[src:arch-linux/source-code] Higher quality code reduces lifetime cost to both suppliers and customers as via higher reliability and maintainability.
[src:arch-linux/source-code] Maintainability is the quality of software enabling it to be easily modified without breaking extant functions.
[src:arch-linux/source-code] Following coding conventions such as using clear function and variable names that correspond to their purpose makes maintenance easier.
[src:arch-linux/source-code] Use of conditional loop statements only if the code could execute more than once, and eliminating code that will never execute can also increase understandability.
[src:arch-linux/source-code] Many software development organizations neglect maintainability during the development phase, even though it will increase long-term costs.
[src:arch-linux/source-code] Technical debt is incurred when programmers, often out of laziness or urgency to meet a deadline, choose quick and dirty solutions rather than build maintainability into their code.
[src:arch-linux/source-code] A common cause is underestimates in software development effort estimation, leading to insufficient resources allocated to development.
[src:arch-linux/source-code] A challenge with maintainability is that many software engineering courses do not emphasize it.
[src:arch-linux/source-code] Development engineers who know that they will not be responsible for maintaining the software do not have an incentive to build in maintainability.
[src:arch-linux/source-code] The situation varies worldwide, but in the United States before 1974, software and its source code was not copyrightable and therefore always public domain software.
[src:arch-linux/source-code] In 1974, the US Commission on New Technological Uses of Copyrighted Works (CONTU) decided that "computer programs, to the extent that they embody an author's original creation, are proper subject matter of copyright".
[src:arch-linux/source-code] Proprietary software is rarely distributed as source code.
[src:arch-linux/source-code] The free reusability of open-source software can speed up development.
